title: Plummer home at 1523 13th Ave., ca. 1914
description: The 1914 Seattle City Directory lists Madge Plummer at 1523 13th Ave. Her husband is listed as F. Howard, a music teacher. A sign on the house window advertises "F. Howard Plummer, Piano Teacher."

title: Sunset Bridge from Great Northern Railway Bridge, ca. 1910
description: The Sunset Mine, located near Index, Washington, operated between 1897 and 1946 producing gold, silver and copper. After Arthur C. Egbert staked his claim in 1897, the Sunset Mining Company was formed to manage operation of the mine.

title: Harry Martin home, ca. 1910
description: There are several men by the name of Harry Martin listed in the 1910 Seattle City Directory: Harry Martin boarding at C717 1/2 Pine; Harry Martin, bookkeeper, boarding at 200 N. 47th; Harry Martin, engineer, house at 5007 2nd Ave. NW; Harry Martin, manager of Eagle Theatre, boarding at 3810 Sunnyside Ave.; Harry Martin, of Martin & Todd lawyers, boarding at 907 Boren Ave, offices at 605-606 Lumber Exchange.

title: Piper home at 1504 18th Ave., ca. 1909
description: The address for this home is 1504 18th Ave. The 1910 Seattle City Directory lists Walter F. Piper, vice president of Piper & [William B.] Taft Inc., as the resident at this address. Also living at this address in 1910 are Minnie Piper, his mother; and Matilda and Lillian Piper, his sisters. His father, Seattle pioneer Andrew W. Piper, died in 1904.

title: Judd, ca. 1910

The oldest of these men, Judd Fish, would have been 58 in 1910 which seems to be younger than the man pictured in the photograph.

description: Transcribed from duplicate photograph: "Parks. Woodland park. Farm house. 1891. At that time the private estate of Guy Phinney."

title: 1st Ave. looking south from Madison St., ca. 1878
description: The caption on the photograph "Front St looking south from Denny Hill" provides the wrong location. The actual location shows the view south on Front St. (now 1st Ave.) from Madison St. Seattle pioneer A.W. Piper appears on the left with his son Walter and their dog, Jim.

title: James St. and Yesler Way, ca. 1867
description: Intersection of James St., Front St. (now 1st Ave.) and Mill St. (now Yesler Way). The Daily Post building appears on the right. The three trees located in front of the building were used for a lynching on January 18, 1882. Buildings on the left side include the Occidental Hotel, the Vanity Fair Saloon, Frach grocery store, Mackintosh and Reeves Bank, Gem Saloon (Charlie Anderson, proprietor) and a drug store (Gardner Kellogg).

title: Woodland Park gazebo, 1891
description: Transcribed from duplicate photograph: "Parks. Woodland park. Gazebo. 1891. At that time the private estate of Guy Phinney."

title: Fauntleroy Church Sunday School class, 1908
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Francis Whalley. 1908. Lois Waterhouse holding Marguerite Marsolais. Helen Goodman. Frances holding? Boy with glasses: Kenneth Colman. Girl in plaid dress: Katherine Colman with Isabel Colman on her right. Blond boy in center: Jim Ben Lynch. Alice --2nd girl on left in front row. Fauntleroy Church 1st Sunday School."

title: Librarian checking out books at Central Library, June 6, 1953
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Mrs. D. D. Gillispie [Gillespie] (librarian) checks in books in main lobby. Mrs. A. F. Pripp. Mr. Harold Simmons." The 1953 city directory lists a Dewey D. Gillespie with a wife named Jean K. The 1953 Library Circulation Department report confirms that Jean worked at the library as a clerk. The city directory also lists Margaret Pripp, wife to Alvin F. Pripp.

title: Bakery and Confectionery Workers Union local no. 9, ca. 1903
description: 1903 appears to be the first year where the Bakers and Confectioners Union is listed in the Seattle City Directory. Prior to that, only a Bakers union was listed.
subjects: Bakery and Confectionary Workers. Union Local 9 (Seattle, Wash.)

title: Women walking on Green Lake path, ca. 1900
Alfred Wotkyns Seymour, May 3, 1922
description: Seymour owned the Alley Kat Cafe and the Woman's Exchange restaurant.

title: View south from near 3rd Ave. and Pike St., ca. 1878
description: The Territorial University, built in 1861, appears on the left at 4th Ave. and University St. According to information on a duplicate photo (spl_shp_5118) the photograph was taken from Third Avenue and Pike Street.

title: Lake Washington Floating Bridge, ca. 1940
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Lake Washington Floating Bridge. Seattle's unique floating bridge is the only one of its kind in the world. Made up of floating concrete sections, each 315 feet in length, the entire floating portion of the bridge measures more than one mile."
subjects: Lacey V. Murrow Bridge (Mercer Island and Seattle, Wash.)

title: Green Lake Branch, Seattle Public Library, May 22, 1991
subjects: Seattle Public Library. Green Lake Branch
East Green Lake Drive North (Seattle, Wash.)

title: Robert (Bob) Nichols, radio announcer, ca. 1927
description: Transcribed from spl_shp_40468: "Robert Nichols. All radio listeners are familiar with the bluff, hearty voice of "Bob" Nichols, chief announcer for the American Broadcasting Company's Seattle studios. Beginning his radio career as a singer several year[s] ago, Nichols then took up announcing sports and finally was appointed chain announcer. He was born in St. Paul, Minnesota, twenty-nine years ago and is over six feet in height, weighing slightly more than two hundred pounds. He was a football, baseball and basketball star at the University of Washington and has covered all of the big Pacific Coast Conference football games for the ABC Network." Nichols is featured in the book ""Seattle Radio"" with the following description: ""Bob Nichols started as a singer on the P.I. Station KFC in 1921. By 1927, he was KJR's sports director and doing some of Seattle's first play-by-play broadcasts.""

title: David and Catherine Maynard home, ca. 1852
description: Transcribed from image: "Early Home of Mrs. D.S. [Catherine] Maynard. Built by Dr. D[avid] S. Maynard in 1852 on the corner of Commercial [later 1st Ave. S.] and Main St. and occupied by him with the first store. It was also the first place of residence of himself and wife. First election in King County was held there, and first Court of Justice of the Peace."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Main St.

title: 1st Ave. S. north from S. Washington St., 1870
description: Commercial St. (now 1st Ave. S.) north from S. Washington St. businesses depicted include the Northwestern Land Agency, Pinkham's Variety Store and Eureka Bakery.
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Washington St.

title: Damaged Seattle streetcar, December 31, 1919
description: Transcribed from similar photograph (spl_shp_40499): "Streetcar (Seattle Municipal Railway #726) at Fremont showing damage from accident at 66th and Phinney Ave, Dec. 31, 1919"
intersection: N. 66th St. and Phinney Ave. N.

title: Broadway High School All-City Orchestra, 1939-1940
description: Broadway High School (then named the Seattle High School) opened in 1902. The high school closed in 1946 and reopened as the Broadway-Edison Technical School. The Edison Technical School incorporated with the Seattle Central Community College in 1966. The only original school structure that still stands as of 2017 is the Performance Hall.

title: Construction of Waterfront Park, June 26, 1974
description: Construction of Seattle's new Waterfront Park on Elliott Bay. June 26, 1974.

title: Greenwood Library open house at new building, January 21, 1954
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Open House at new structure. Many children crowd into the Greenwood Branch Library for a look at familiar books on new shelves as the branch holds "open house" following its dedication. Building, located at 8016 Greenwood Ave. is Seattle's first public library branch to be constructed in 33 years."

title: Homes at 5316, 5312 and 5308 Green Lake Way N., August 3, 1927
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Looking east across East Green Lake Way near N 54th St. Aug 3, 1927." Houses pictured from left to right are 5316, 5312 and 5308 E. Green Lake Way N.
intersection: N. 54th St. and Green Lake Way N.

title: R. Metz and Church in Israel member discussing the body of the Church's leader, Daniel Sawlt's, June 1929
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Religion and Sanitation Clash in Seattle. Seattle, Wash. A member of "The Church in Israel" talking with R. Metz of the Seattle Sanitation and Health Department following Metz's demand that the body of Daniel Salwt, prophet of the Israel organization be removed from their church and taken to an undertaking establishment. The disciples had refused to have the body touched saying it would interfere with resurrection. The dispute ended when the churchmen allowed the body to be removed on condition that it would not be embalmed for a certain period and that they be allowed to watch over it. R-6-20-29. EHP."

title: Seattle World's Fair truck advertisement, ca. 1962
description: Location of the truck appears to be Coronado, California. Identities of the men photographed are unknown.

title: John Muir Elementary Drum and Bugle Corps, March 1, 1932
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Presented to Mr. Knutsen by the John Muir Drum and Bugle Corps, March 21, 1932."

title: Green Lake and Phinney's Boathouse from Woodland Park, 1891
description: The boathouse was located on the SW shore of Green Lake. Prior to the lowering of the lake, the southern shoreline extended as far south as NE 55th St.

title: Woodland Park entrance lodge, 1891
description: Transcribed from duplicate photograph: ""Parks. Woodland park. Entrance lodge. 1891. At that time private estate of Guy Phinney.""
